# .vercelignore (D-02 — LAUNCH-01 / LAUNCH-10)
#
# Vercel uploads the WORKING TREE (not git history) on `vercel --prod`, filtered by THIS
# file (when present it REPLACES .gitignore — they are NOT merged). Vercel then runs
# `next build`, which TYPE-CHECKS the whole tsconfig project. So this file must NOT exclude
# any directory that a type-checked file references.
#
# HARD-LEARNED (launch): excluding code/test dirs broke the Vercel build two ways the local
# build can never catch (because nothing is excluded locally):
#   1. An unanchored `supabase/` recursively matched `src/lib/supabase/` -> 58
#      "Can't resolve '@/lib/supabase/*'" errors.
#   2. `scripts/` ships (the build runs `scripts/check-env.mjs` via prebuild), and
#      `scripts/preview-template.ts` imports from `e2e/` — excluding `e2e/` made the
#      production type-check fail ("Cannot find module '../e2e/helpers/slugs'").
#
# Therefore: exclude ONLY the large, local-only planning corpus and local env/caches. Ship
# everything tracked in git (src/, scripts/, public/, docs/, supabase/, tests/, e2e/,
# next.config.ts, package.json, .env.example). None of docs/supabase/tests/e2e is bundled
# into the runtime — Next.js only bundles what the app actually imports — so shipping them is
# harmless and keeps the Vercel type-check graph IDENTICAL to local. D-03: NO vercel.json
# (CSP/HSTS headers ship in next.config.ts headers() from Phase 16).
#
# DO NOT add scripts/, src/, public/, next.config.ts, package.json, or .env.example here.

# The large, local-only planning corpus. It is gitignored locally, but Vercel uploads the
# working tree (not git history), so it WOULD ship unless excluded here.
/.planning/

# Local env files + caches — re-covered here because .vercelignore replaces .gitignore.
# .env.local is the belt-and-suspenders secret-leak guard (T-23-04).
.env.local
.env.*.local
*.log
.lighthouseci/
